<textarea name="{{ name }}" id="{{ id }}" cols="30" rows="10" class="house--ta">{{ value.raw|raw }}</textarea>

<div id="{{ id }}-help" class="house--help-content">
	<div class="header">
		<h1>Markdown Help</h1>
	</div>

	<div class="body">
		{# References #}
		<h2>References</h2>
		<p>To add a reference to your text type <code>{</code>, an auto-complete menu will appear letting you select what type of reference you want to insert. This will then open a modal that will let you select your the element(s) you want to reference.</p>
		<img src="{{ resourceUrl('markdown/imgs/reference-auto-complete.jpg') }}" alt="Reference Auto-complete">

		{# Headings #}
		<h2>Headings</h2>
		<p>You can use up to up to six levels <code>by writing # before</code> a heading; the number of hashes defines the hierarchy of the heading. Don't forget to add a space after the #:</p>

		<pre><code># First level heading
## Second level heading
### Third level heading</code></pre>

		{# Emphasis & Importance #}
		<h2>Emphasis and Importance</h2>
		<p>Emphasis ("italics") and important ("bold") are written by putting * or _ around the text you want to see in a different format.</p>

		<ul>
			<li>Emphasis: <code>*example*</code> or <code>_example_</code></li>
			<li>Importance: <code>**example**</code> or <code>__example__</code></li>
			<li>Emphasis + Importance: <code>***example***</code> or <code>___example___</code></li>
		</ul>

		{# Numbered Lists #}
		<h2>Numbered Lists</h2>
		<p>Type <code>1.</code> then a space. Any number (followed by a full stop and space) can be used and the list items will be ordered from 1 when displayed.</p>

		<pre><code>1. Ordered list item
2. Ordered list item
3. Ordered list item</code></pre>

		{# Bulleted Lists #}
		<h2>Bulleted lists</h2>
		<p>Type <code>*</code>, <code>-</code> or <code>+</code> then a space. Create a bulleted list by using an asterisk (*), hyphen (-), or plus sign (+), followed by a space.</p>

		<pre><code>* Bulleted list item
* Bulleted list item
* Bulleted list item</code></pre>

		{# Nesting Lists #}
		<h2>Nesting lists</h2>
		<p>You can nest lists by tab indenting them:</p>

		<pre><code>* First level
  * Second level

1. First level
  1. Second level</code></pre>

		{# Blockquotes #}
		<h2>Blockquotes</h2>
		<p>Type <code>></code> plus a space:</p>

		<pre><code>> A quoted paragraph
>> A quoted paragraph inside a quotation</code></pre>

		{# Links #}
		<h2>Links</h2>
		<p>Create a link by surrounding the link text in square brackets, followed immediately by the URL in parentheses:</p>

		<pre><code>[text to link](http://example.com/)</code></pre>

		<p>You can also use reference links. Add the reference in square brackets after the text to link. Then, on a line by itself add the reference with a colon, space, and the URL:</p>

		<pre><code>[text to link][ref]
…
[ref]: http://example.com/</code></pre>

		{# Images #}
		<h2>Images</h2>
		<p>Create an image by typing an <code>!</code> followed by the images alt text surrounded by square brackets, and the URL and title (in quotation marks) of the image in parentheses after that:</p>

		<pre><code>![image alt text]({asset:135} "Image title")</code></pre>

		<p>As with links, you can also use a reference:</p>

		<pre><code>![image alt text][ref]
…
[ref]: http://example.com/image.png "Image Title"</code></pre>

		{# Code #}
		<h2>Code</h2>
		<p>You can mark up code in-line using backticks (<code>`code`</code>), or add a code block by adding at least four spaces to the start of a line:</p>

		<pre><code>    This is a code block</code></pre>

		<p>It's also possible to start a code block with a tab, as long as the text doesn’t start with list, header or blockquote syntax characters (<code>1.</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>+</code>, <code>#</code>, <code>></code>).</p>

		<p>In addition, you can use Fenced code blocks, which begin and end with triple backticks, and don’t need indenting. Note that inline formatting (like <code>_underscores_</code>) is ignored in code.</p>
		<p>If you are using a syntax highlighter, you can specifiy the language by name immediately after the opening three backticks.</p>

		<pre><code>```javascript
var myVariable = 12;
```</code></pre>

		{# Footnotes #}
		<h2>Footnotes</h2>
		<p>Add a footnote in square brackets preceded by a caret. Then add the footnote content like a reference link, for example:</p>

		<pre><code>Some text[^footRef] with a footnote[^1].
…
[^1]: The linked footnote appears at the end of the output.
[^footRef]: The footnotes will be listed in the order they were added to the document</code></pre>

		<p>You can also add an inline footnote in the following manner:</p>

		<pre><code>Some text with a footnote[^This is the footnote itself.].</code></pre>

		{# Tables #}
		<h2>Tables</h2>
		<p>To make a table, use vertical bar characters to denote cells. Start with column headers, separate with a row of cells with hyphens, then add further rows of cells. For example:</p>

		<pre><code>|Header |Column 1 | Column 2 | Column 3  |
| ----- |:------- |:--------:| ---------:|
|1. Row | is      | is       | is        |
|2. Row | left    | nicely   | right     |
|3. Row | aligned | centered | aligned   |</code></pre>

		{# Horizontal rules #}
		<h2>Horizontal rules</h2>
		<p>You can add a thematic break which will be represented by a dividing line (<code>&lt;hr></code>) when exported to HTML. To do so, add three or more asterisks (<code>*</code>), hyphens (<code>-</code>), or underscores (<code>_</code>) on a line by themselves, optionally separated with spaces. For example:</p>

		<pre><code>* * *</code></pre>

		<p>or</p>

		<pre><code>-------------</code></pre>

		{# Escaping #}
		<h2>"Escaping" formatting characters</h2>
		<p>If you want to type a formatting character and have Writer treat it as text not formatting, type a backslash first <code>\</code>. This means <code>\*</code> gives <code>*</code>, <code>\_</code> gives <code>_</code> etc. Escaping isn't needed in code blocks.</p>

		{# HTML #}
		<h2>HTML</h2>
		<p>You can insert any HTML into your markdown and it will be parsed as normal. This is useful if you need to insert an embed like a video, gist, etc.</p>

		{# Markdown Extra #}
		<h2>Markdown Extra</h2>
		<p><a href="https://michelf.ca/projects/php-markdown/extra/" target="_blank">Markdown Extra</a> is also supported, and contains extended functionality that isn't listed here.</p>
	</div>

	<div class="footer">
		<div class="buttons right last">
			<input type="button" class="btn cancel" value="Close">
		</div>
	</div>
</div>